# Monte Carlo Numerical Integration

## Background

Monte Carlo integration is a probabilistic method for estimating the value of a definite integral. The core idea is to enclose the function of interest inside a known rectangle, then randomly sample points within that rectangle. The proportion of points that fall on or below the curve, multiplied by the area of the rectangle, provides an estimate of the integral.

For this analysis, I was assigned the standard normal probability density function (PDF):

$$f(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} e^{-x^2/2}$$

evaluated over the interval $[-4, 4]$ with $y$ values bounded by $[0, 0.4]$. The theoretical value of $\int_{-4}^{4} f(x) \, dx$ is extremely close to 1 (approximately 0.99994).

## Monte Carlo Simulation Function

```{r}
#| label: mc-function

# Monte Carlo Simulation Function ----
# Generates n random (x, y) points within a specified rectangle
mcSimulation <- function(n, xMin, xMax, yMin, yMax) {
  data.frame(
    x = runif(n, min = xMin, max = xMax),
    y = runif(n, min = yMin, max = yMax)
  )
}
```

## Small Multiple Visualization

@fig-mc-small-multiples displays the Monte Carlo simulation at four different resolutions: $n = 10$, $n = 100$, $n = 1{,}000$, and $n = 10{,}000$. Each panel shows the random points colored by whether they fall on/below the standard normal density curve or above it, along with the resulting integral estimate. The four panels were created as individual `ggplot` objects and combined into a single figure using the `{patchwork}` package, following the approach described in @hatfieldQuartoCrashCourse.

```{r}
#| label: fig-mc-small-multiples
#| fig-cap: "Monte Carlo Integration of the Standard Normal PDF at Four Resolutions"
#| fig-pos: H
#| fig-height: 7
#| fig-width: 9

# Set seed for reproducibility ----
set.seed(184)

# Rectangle bounds ----
xMin <- -4
xMax <- 4
yMin <- 0
yMax <- 0.4
rectArea <- (xMax - xMin) * (yMax - yMin)

# Helper function to build a single MC plot for a given n ----
makeMCPlot <- function(n) {
  simData <- mcSimulation(n, xMin, xMax, yMin, yMax)

  mcResults <- simData |>
    mutate(
      curveY = dnorm(x),
      flag = if_else(y <= curveY, "on/below", "above")
    )

  estIntegral <- rectArea * mean(mcResults$flag == "on/below")

  ggplot(mcResults, aes(x = x, y = y, color = flag)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.7, size = 1.2) +
    stat_function(fun = dnorm, linewidth = 1, color = "navy") +
    scale_color_manual(values = c("on/below" = "steelblue", "above" = "coral")) +
    coord_cartesian(xlim = c(xMin, xMax), ylim = c(yMin, yMax)) +
    labs(
      title = paste0("Monte Carlo Integration, n = ", format(n, big.mark = ",")),
      subtitle = paste("Estimated Integral =", round(estIntegral, 4)),
      x = "x",
      y = "y",
      color = "flag"
    ) +
    theme_minimal()
}

# Build the four plots at different resolutions ----
plot10    <- makeMCPlot(10)
plot100   <- makeMCPlot(100)
plot1000  <- makeMCPlot(1000)
plot10000 <- makeMCPlot(10000)

# Combine into small multiple with {patchwork} ----
(plot10 + plot100) / (plot1000 + plot10000) +
  plot_layout(guides = "collect") &
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")
```

A few things become clear from the small multiple. At $n = 10$, the estimate is unreliable and fluctuates wildly from run to run because there simply aren't enough sampled points to cover the rectangle. At $n = 100$, the bell shape starts to emerge but the estimate is still noisy. By $n = 1{,}000$, the curve is clearly visible and the estimate lands close to the true value. At $n = 10{,}000$, the density of points makes the standard normal curve obvious, and the estimate is very close to 1.

The exact value of $\int_{-4}^{4} \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}} e^{-x^2/2} \, dx$ is approximately 0.99994 — essentially 1, since the bounds $[-4, 4]$ capture nearly all of the area under the standard normal density. The small multiple supports this reasoning because as $n$ grows, the estimate converges toward 1, which is exactly what the law of large numbers predicts. Someone looking at the $n = 10{,}000$ panel could reach the same conclusion: the estimate sits right around 1, and the visible curve matches the known shape of the standard normal PDF.

