# Planning and Prompting GenAI Tools

## Data Context and Plan

The dataset for this section is `calcium.csv`, which comes from a longitudinal study that followed 31 women over four years. Researchers measured ulnar calcium levels (via photon absorptiometry) at the start of the study and then once a year for the next three years. Fifteen of the women formed a null treatment group and received no intervention. The other sixteen formed a diet/exercise treatment group and followed a structured diet and exercise program over the four years.

The CSV file stores the data in a non-tidy format. There are eight columns, all named `y0`, `y1`, `y2`, `y3`, `y0`, `y1`, `y2`, `y3`. The first four columns hold the null treatment group and the last four hold the diet/exercise group. Each row is one woman. Because the null group has one fewer subject than the diet/exercise group, one row has `NA` values in the first four columns. Two things make this data not tidy: the year of measurement is encoded in column names rather than a column of its own, and the treatment group is encoded by column position instead of being a variable.

Before prompting any GenAI tool, I worked out the following plan:

1. Read `calcium.csv` into R, handling the duplicate column names by assigning unique names on import (for example, `y0_null, y1_null, y2_null, y3_null, y0_de, y1_de, y2_de, y3_de`).
2. Add a subject ID column so each woman can be tracked through time.
3. Split the data into two frames, one per treatment group, and tag each with a `treatment` column (`null` or `diet_exercise`). Drop the row that has all `NA` values in the null group.
4. Stack the two frames with `bind_rows()` so treatment becomes a variable with two levels instead of a difference in columns.
5. Use `pivot_longer()` to reshape the year columns into a single `year` column and a single `calcium` column. Strip the leading `y` from the year values and convert them to numeric.
6. Build a plot that compares the two treatment groups over time. A reasonable choice is a line plot showing each woman's trajectory (grouped by subject, colored by treatment) with a thicker summary line for each group's average per year, so individual variation and the group-level trend are both visible.

## Results from Plan-Based Prompt

I used the plan above along with the unaltered `calcium.csv` file as a prompt to Anthropic Claude. The exact prompt and response are documented in Appendix A. The code Claude produced is shown below.

```
The R script follows your six steps exactly. A few notes on choices I made where the plan had small ambiguities:

Step 1 uses read_csv(..., name_repair = "unique"), which renames the duplicates to y0...1, y1...2, ..., y0...5, y1...6, .... In step 3 I select those by position (select(subject, y0 = 1, ...)) and rename back to y0/y1/y2/y3 in each split, which keeps the downstream pivot_longer clean.
Step 3 drops the all-NA row using filter(!if_all(starts_with("y"), is.na)). After the filter the null group has 15 rows as expected.
I offset the treatment group's subject IDs by max(null_group$subject) so each woman has a globally unique ID — otherwise subject 1 in the null group and subject 1 in the diet/exercise group would collide when grouping by subject in the plot.
Step 6 computes group means separately and overlays them as thick lines with larger points. The individual trajectories use alpha = 0.35 so the means read as the dominant summary.

library(tidyverse)

# Step 1: Read CSV with unique column names to handle the duplicates
calcium_raw <- read_csv(
  "/mnt/user-data/uploads/calcium.csv",
  name_repair = "unique"
)

# Step 2: Add a subject ID column
calcium_raw <- calcium_raw |>
  mutate(subject = row_number())

# Step 3: Split into the two treatment groups, tag them, drop the all-NA row
null_group <- calcium_raw |>
  select(subject, y0 = 1, y1 = 2, y2 = 3, y3 = 4) |>
  mutate(treatment = "null") |>
  filter(!if_all(starts_with("y"), is.na))

trt_group <- calcium_raw |>
  select(subject, y0 = 5, y1 = 6, y2 = 7, y3 = 8) |>
  mutate(treatment = "diet_exercise")

# Give the treatment group distinct subject IDs so they don't collide with null group IDs
trt_group <- trt_group |>
  mutate(subject = subject + max(null_group$subject))

# Step 4: Stack the two frames
calcium <- bind_rows(null_group, trt_group)

# Step 5: Pivot longer, strip the "y", convert year to numeric
calcium_long <- calcium |>
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("y"),
    names_to = "year",
    values_to = "calcium"
  ) |>
  mutate(
    year = as.numeric(str_remove(year, "^y")),
    treatment = factor(treatment, levels = c("null", "diet_exercise"))
  )

# Step 6: Plot — individual trajectories plus group means
group_means <- calcium_long |>
  group_by(treatment, year) |>
  summarise(calcium = mean(calcium), .groups = "drop")

p <- ggplot(calcium_long, aes(x = year, y = calcium, color = treatment)) +
  geom_line(aes(group = subject), alpha = 0.35) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.4, size = 1.5) +
  geom_line(
    data = group_means,
    aes(group = treatment),
    linewidth = 1.6
  ) +
  geom_point(
    data = group_means,
    size = 3
  ) +
  scale_color_manual(
    values = c("null" = "#2C7FB8", "diet_exercise" = "#D95F02"),
    labels = c("null" = "Null", "diet_exercise" = "Diet & exercise")
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Ulnar calcium over four years by treatment group",
    subtitle = "Thin lines: individual women. Thick lines: group mean per year.",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Ulnar calcium",
    color = "Treatment"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    legend.position = "bottom"
  )

ggsave(
  "/home/claude/calcium_plot.png",
  p,
  width = 8,
  height = 5.5,
  dpi = 150,
  bg = "white"
)

print(p)
cat("\nLong-format data preview:\n")
print(head(calcium_long, 10))
cat("\nDimensions:", nrow(calcium_long), "rows x", ncol(calcium_long), "cols\n")
cat("Subjects per group:\n")
print(calcium_long |> distinct(subject, treatment) |> count(treatment))
```

