A couple of notes on judgment calls that come up when executing this plan literally:

Reading duplicate column names. read_csv with name_repair = "unique" keeps all eight columns by suffixing the duplicates (y0...1, y0...5, etc.). I then select by position in step 3 and rename to clean y0..y3 within each group, which is cleaner than trying to parse the suffixed names.
Subject IDs. Using row_number() on the raw frame means null subject 1 and treatment subject 1 share an ID. That's fine because they're in different groups, but I used interaction(subject, treatment) in geom_line's group aesthetic so lines never bridge groups. If you'd rather have globally unique IDs, generate them separately inside each of the two frames in step 3.
Dropping the NA row. if_all(starts_with("y"), is.na) drops the row only when all four null-group columns are NA — safer than a blanket drop_na(), which would also nuke any partial-missing observation you might want to keep.
