## Comparison of Plan-Based vs. Generic Prompts

Both prompts produced working tidyverse solutions that executed the plan correctly and generated nearly identical plots. The main difference is how they handled subject IDs. The plan-based version offsets the treatment group's IDs by max(null_group$subject) so every woman has a globally unique ID. The generic version leaves both groups sharing IDs 1–15 and patches it in the plot with interaction(subject, treatment). Both work, but fixing it in the data is cleaner than relying on the plot call to sort it out.

The plan-based response also checked the CSV before writing code and rendered a preview, while the generic one wrote code blind. Both flagged the same judgment calls — using if_all(starts_with("y"), is.na) instead of drop_na(), choosing alpha = 0.35 for the individual lines — but the generic version is slightly tighter in a few spots, like chaining the factor conversion into bind_rows.

The bigger takeaway is that code quality was basically equivalent; what differed was fit. The plan-based output matched what I actually wanted with no revisions needed. The generic version would work, but I'd want to tweak it before using it. Giving the tool a plan meant it spent its effort on the small decisions inside that plan rather than guessing at the plan itself.

