# Reflection

Before this course, most of my experience with data came from whatever side project I was trying to build at the time. I would scrape prices off websites, parse API responses, drop results into a spreadsheet, and move on. STAT 184 has pushed me to slow down and think about the shape of the data itself before I start pulling things out of it, and looking back at old code I have written, I can see a lot of places I made things harder for myself because I skipped that step.

Tidy data is the idea that has changed how I actually work. I had been fighting messy spreadsheets for years without having a name for the problems I kept running into. The first time I read the tidy data chapter in @kaplanDataComputing, I went back to a tracking script I was using for prediction market trades and realized I had built half the script around working around the fact that I had stored time as columns rather than rows. Rewriting it as tidy data cut the script in half. That was the moment I started trusting the framework instead of treating it as an academic rule.

The `ggplot2` grammar of graphics took longer to click, and I struggled with it more than I expected to. My first few plots looked bad because I was using `ggplot2` the way I use matplotlib — as a set of one-off drawing commands. I kept wondering why simple things felt harder than they should, and the answer was that I was fighting the grammar instead of using it. Once I stopped treating each line as a separate command and started thinking about plots as aesthetics mapped to geoms with scales and labels layered on top, the syntax started working for me instead of against me. The busiest airports plot in this assignment is the first time I built a multi-series plot where I did not have to stop and look something up midway through.

The Monte Carlo assignment was the most interesting thing we have covered so far, but it also exposed a gap in my thinking. The underlying idea — estimate something you cannot compute directly by sampling and taking a proportion — shows up in prediction markets and sports betting models, which are things I already spend time on. What I did not fully appreciate before was how much the variance of the estimate depends on the sample size. Watching the estimate at $n = 10$ jump around by large amounts from one run to the next, compared to how stable the estimate was at $n = 10{,}000$, gave me a concrete intuition for the law of large numbers that I had only understood in the abstract. It also made me more careful about small-sample estimates in my own work, where I had been too quick to trust early results.

Quarto is the last piece I did not expect to care about and now use the most. I was skeptical at first because I have written code files and markdown files separately for years and the workflow was fine. What changed my mind was moving my HW 3.4 work into this Quarto document for HW 4.3. Re-rendering the document forced me to re-run every piece of code from scratch, and I caught at least two places where my local environment had drifted out of sync with what was actually in my script. If I had only been looking at the output I had already generated, I would not have caught those. The code appendix pattern using `ref.label=knitr::all_labels()` is the part I plan to use on any future project where someone else needs to read my work.

